INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c24321af-4c1c-4a03-9a8c-2c0bb62755ec',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$scikit-learn MLPClassifier — Diagnosing NaN Loss and Gradient Instability$escape$,
  $escape$scikit-learn's `MLPClassifier` and `MLPRegressor` are the only estimators where gradient dynamics directly affect training. NaN appearing in `clf.loss_curve_` after fitting almost always signals exploding gradients — inspect it immediately.

The most common culprit is unscaled features. scikit-learn's MLP has no internal normalization. Always prepend a `StandardScaler` in a `Pipeline`. Second suspect: `learning_rate_init`. The default `0.001` is stable with `solver='adam'`, but `solver='sgd'` with the same init frequently diverges on high-variance data.

For vanishing gradients, watch for a flat `loss_curve_` after the first 5–10 epochs. Switch `activation` from `'relu'` (prone to dead neurons under poor initialization) to `'tanh'` in shallow nets, or widen `hidden_layer_sizes`. On small datasets, `solver='lbfgs'` sidesteps gradient issues entirely — it's a second-order optimizer with no learning rate or momentum to tune.

Always enable `verbose=True` to stream per-epoch loss during development. Combine with `early_stopping=True` and `validation_fraction=0.1` to catch divergence well before `max_iter` is exhausted.$escape$,
  $escape$import numpy as np
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

pipe = Pipeline([
    ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
    ("mlp", MLPClassifier(
        hidden_layer_sizes=(128, 64),
        activation="relu",
        solver="adam",
        learning_rate_init=0.001,
        max_iter=200,
        early_stopping=True,
        verbose=True,
    )),
])
pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)

loss = pipe.named_steps["mlp"].loss_curve_
if any(np.isnan(loss)):
    print("NaN detected — reduce learning_rate_init or verify feature scaling")$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
