INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '50701392-dfe6-40ab-a62e-7c2d0e7ca7dd',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$scikit-learn Model Evaluation — Picking the Right Metric for Every Task$escape$,
  $escape$scikit-learn's `metrics` module maps cleanly to task type. For classification, `accuracy_score` misleads on imbalanced data — reach for `f1_score(average='macro')` or `classification_report()` which prints precision, recall, and F1 per class in one call. `confusion_matrix()` returns a raw array; pair it with `ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_estimator()` to skip the manual plotting boilerplate. For regression, `mean_squared_error(squared=False)` gives RMSE directly; `r2_score()` measures explained variance. For probabilistic outputs, `roc_auc_score()` and `log_loss()` reward well-calibrated probabilities rather than hard predictions.

Cross-validation is the real safety net. `cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=5, scoring='f1_macro')` runs stratified k-fold by default for classifiers. For more control, `cross_validate()` returns fit time, score time, and multiple metrics simultaneously. Use `StratifiedKFold` explicitly when class imbalance is severe, or `GroupKFold` when samples share a group identity (e.g., same user, same patient). Never tune hyperparameters on the cross-val fold — wrap the whole pipeline in `GridSearchCV` so the split is clean.$escape$,
  $escape$from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate, StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay, classification_report
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)

results = cross_validate(
    model, X, y, cv=cv,
    scoring=['f1_macro', 'roc_auc_ovr'],
    return_train_score=True
)
print(results['test_f1_macro'].mean(), results['test_roc_auc_ovr'].mean())

model.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(classification_report(y_test, model.predict(X_test)))
ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_estimator(model, X_test, y_test)
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
