INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c4370db9-747f-45d2-b07d-7a3d7b487748',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$scikit-learn in Production — ONNX Export, Joblib Pitfalls, and Serving That Actually Works$escape$,
  $escape$Shipping a scikit-learn model to production has two credible paths: joblib serialization or ONNX export. Joblib is fast to set up but tightly couples your serving environment to a specific scikit-learn version — a 1.3 → 1.4 upgrade can silently break deserialization. For cross-language or version-stable serving, convert via skl2onnx: call convert_sklearn() with the estimator and a type_map built from initial_type, then save with onnx.save_model(). The resulting .onnx file runs in any ONNX Runtime environment (Python, C#, Java) with no sklearn dependency.

For inference, use onnxruntime.InferenceSession — it's 2–5× faster than sklearn's predict() on CPU for tabular models due to ahead-of-time graph optimization. Watch for pipelines: skl2onnx supports most built-in transformers (StandardScaler, OrdinalEncoder, SimpleImputer) but chokes on custom FunctionTransformer unless you register a custom converter. Always call sess.run() with a numpy float32 array — float64 inputs cause a silent dtype mismatch that returns wrong predictions, not an error.$escape$,
  $escape$from skl2onnx import convert_sklearn
from skl2onnx.common.data_types import FloatTensorType
import onnx
import onnxruntime as rt
import numpy as np

# Export sklearn Pipeline to ONNX
initial_type = [("float_input", FloatTensorType([None, X_train.shape[1]]))]
onnx_model = convert_sklearn(pipeline, initial_types=initial_type)
onnx.save_model(onnx_model, "model.onnx")

# Inference — note float32, not float64
sess = rt.InferenceSession("model.onnx")
input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
pred = sess.run(None, {input_name: X_test.astype(np.float32)})[0]$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
